					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I'm taking a bit of a break from ascii-&gt;pixels and pixels-&gt;video signal to determine the representation of text as a bitstream. Obviously, a straight 8-bit-per-character encoding is right out, as gzip compresses text at 3:1. But plain old Lempel-Ziv compression doesn't work well because there isn't much RAM inside an NES to hold the ring buffer (for LZ77) or dynamic dictionary (for LZ78). Does anybody know what kind of compression was used for answers and questions in Rare's <em>Jeopardy!</em> games?
<br />
<br />If you can figure out what the heck <a href="http://pics.pineight.com/nes/vwf/003_words.txt" class="postlink">this file</a> represents, you win an e-cookie.</div>

